quarks.connectors.runtime

Class Connector<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • quarks.connectors.runtime.Connector<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - type of the underlying managed connector (e.g., MqttClient)
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.AutoCloseable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    MqttConnector, WebSocketClientConnector

    public abstract class Connector<T>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.lang.AutoCloseable, java.io.Serializable
    An abstract class for general connector connection management.

    The basic (default) model is to maintain a connection across inadvertent disconnects.

    A connected connector is returned whenever client() is called. If the connection is lost, actions are taken to reestablish it. Overall tracking and control of connection state is performed and general logging is performed.

    Sub-classes are able to further control when initial connection occurs and generally expose ways to explicitly disconnect or connect.

    Optionally, clients can request automatic disconnection after a period of inactivity - see setIdleTimeout(long, TimeUnit). Support for this feature requires connector implementations to call notIdle().

    TODO - dynamic control:

    • [abstract] ConnectorControl { getState(), connect(), disconnect(), ...}.
    • MqttConnectorControl extends ConnectorControl. Adds subscribe(), unsubscribe().
    • Add Consumer<MqttConnectorControl> to MqttConfig. Runtime calls it supplying a connector control object. By doing a disconnect()/connect(), the Supplier<MqttConfig> will be called to as part of reconnect -- hence using updated values if any.

    Sub-classes are responsible for implementing a small number of operations: doConnect(Object), doDisconnect(Object), doClose(Object), and id(). Sub-classes are also responsible for calling connectionLost(Throwable) and notIdle().
